The University of Nevada, Reno (often abbreviated as Nevada, the University of Nevada, or UNR) stands as a preeminent [public](/Public_university) [land-grant](/Land-grant_university) [research university](/Research_university) nestled in the vibrant city of [Reno, Nevada](/Reno,_Nevada). It proudly holds the distinction of being the state's flagship institution of higher learning and its primary land grant establishment. Its genesis dates back to October 12, 1874, with its initial founding in [Elko, Nevada](/Elko,_Nevada).

This esteemed university is classified as a [doctoral](/Doctorate), R1 [research university](/Research_university) according to the rigorous criteria set forth by the [Carnegie Classification](/Carnegie_Classification_of_Institutions_of_Higher_Education). The commitment to scholarly advancement is underscored by its substantial investment in research and development, with the university reporting an expenditure of $144 million in this domain during 2018, as documented by the [National Science Foundation](/National_Science_Foundation). Among its diverse array of academic units, the university boasts a distinguished [medical school](/University_of_Nevada,_Reno_School_of_Medicine) and is the proud home of the [Donald W. Reynolds School of Journalism](/Donald_W._Reynolds_School_of_Journalism), an institution that has nurtured six [Pulitzer Prize](/Pulitzer_Prize) laureates among its alumni.

### Former Names

The institution has undergone several name changes throughout its storied existence, reflecting its growth and evolving identity:

*   **State University of Nevada** (1874–1881)
*   **Nevada State University** (1881–1906)
*   **University of Nevada** (1906–1969)

### Motto

The university's guiding principle is encapsulated in its Latin motto, *Omnia Pro Patria*, which translates to "All for Our Country" in English. This motto speaks to a deep-seated commitment to public service and national betterment.

### Type

University of Nevada, Reno operates as a [public](/Public_university), [land-grant](/Land-grant_university), and [research university](/Research_university).

### Establishment and Affiliations

The university was officially established on October 12, 1874, marking a significant milestone in Nevada's educational landscape. It operates under the umbrella of the [Nevada System of Higher Education](/Nevada_System_of_Higher_Education). Its academic standing is affirmed by its accreditation through the [NWCCU](/Northwest_Commission_on_Colleges_and_Universities). Furthermore, it holds affiliations with prestigious organizations such as [ORAU](/Oak_Ridge_Associated_Universities) and participates in the [Space-grant](/National_Space_Grant_College_and_Fellowship_Program).

### Financials and Leadership

As of 2024, the university's [endowment](/Financial_endowment) stands at an impressive $560.1 million. The current [President](/University_president) of the University of Nevada, Reno is [Brian Sandoval](/Brian_Sandoval), with Jeff Thompson serving as [Provost](/Provost_(education)).

### Faculty and Student Body

The university is home to a robust academic staff of 1,082 individuals. As of the fall of 2022, it enrolled a total of 20,945 students. This figure comprises 16,973 [undergraduates](/Undergraduate_education) and 3,972 [postgraduates](/Postgraduate_education), reflecting a diverse and dynamic student population.

### Location and Campus

The main campus of the University of Nevada, Reno is situated in [Reno, Nevada](/Reno,_Nevada), United States. It occupies a substantial area, with the main campus spanning 200 acres (81 ha). The university also maintains other campuses, including one in [Incline Village](/Sierra_Nevada_University).

### Student Newspaper

The university's student newspaper, a vital organ of campus communication and student voice, is known as [The Nevada Sagebrush](/The_Nevada_Sagebrush).

### School Colors and Athletic Identity

The official [Colors](/School_colors) of the University of Nevada, Reno are navy blue and silver. Its athletic teams are famously known by their [Nickname](/Athletic_nickname) as the [Wolf Pack](/Nevada_Wolf_Pack).

### Sporting Affiliations

In the realm of collegiate sports, the Wolf Pack competes in [NCAA Division I FBS](/NCAA_Division_I_FBS), primarily within the [Mountain West](/Mountain_West_Conference) conference.

### Mascots

The spirited mascots representing the Wolf Pack are Alphie, Wolfie Jr., and Luna, embodying the university's athletic prowess and camaraderie.

### Website

The official online presence of the University of Nevada, Reno can be found at www.unr.edu.

### University of Nevada Historic District

A significant portion of the university's architectural heritage is recognized by its inclusion in the [U.S. National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) as a [U.S. Historic district](/Historic_districts_in_the_United_States). This district, encompassing 290 acres (117.4 ha) of the entire campus, with a designated historic area of 40 acres (16 ha), showcases a rich architectural tapestry. Built primarily from 1906 onwards, the architectural styles represented include [Late 19th and 20th Century Revivals](/Late_19th_and_20th_Century_Revivals_architecture), [Second Empire](/Second_Empire_architecture), and Jeffersonian Revival. The district was officially added to the NRHP on February 25, 1987, under reference number 87000135.

### History

The foundational act of establishing a university within the [Nevada state constitution](/Constitution_of_Nevada) was enshrined in 1864, a provision that would enable the state to leverage funds from the [Morrill Act](/Morrill_Land-Grant_Acts). Thus, on October 12, 1874, the State University of Nevada was brought into being in [Elko, Nevada](/Elko,_Nevada). By 1881, its name had evolved to Nevada State University. A pivotal moment arrived in 1885 when the university relocated from Elko to Reno. This move was necessitated by consistently low enrollment figures, which never surpassed 35 students, and a prevailing trend among families to send their children to educational institutions in California. [^9^] The acquisition of land for the university site north of Reno was facilitated by local rancher John Newton "Newt" Evans, who sold the property for $1,250. [^11^] The cornerstone of the campus, [Morrill Hall,](/Morrill_Hall_(University_of_Nevada,_Reno)) was dedicated in 1886, bearing the name of [Justin Morrill](/Justin_S._Morrill), the architect of the legislation that provided crucial funding for the university. Instruction commenced in 1887 with an inaugural class of fifty students. [^12^]

In 1906, the institution was renamed the University of Nevada. [^12^] For a considerable period, the University of Nevada stood as the sole four-year academic institution within the state. This remained the case until 1965, when the Nevada Southern campus, which would later become the [University of Nevada, Las Vegas](/University_of_Nevada,_Las_Vegas), was established as a separate university. To clearly distinguish it from its Las Vegas counterpart, the university's name was changed to the University of Nevada, Reno in 1969. More recently, in 2022, UNR expanded its reach by acquiring the physical assets of the now-defunct [Sierra Nevada University](/Sierra_Nevada_University) in [Incline Village, Nevada](/Incline_Village,_Nevada), establishing the University of Nevada, Reno at Lake Tahoe. [^13^]

