### Campus

The University of Nevada, Reno's main campus is a sprawling expanse located just north of downtown [Reno](/Reno,_Nevada), offering picturesque views of [Truckee Meadows](/Truckee_Meadows) and the city's iconic casinos. As Nevada's premier institution of higher education, it serves as a central hub for academic and cultural life in the state. [^23^]

#### Early Construction

The architectural genesis of the campus is marked by the completion of [Morrill Hall](/Morrill_Hall_(University_of_Nevada,_Reno)) in 1887. This historic building, still standing proudly on the southern end of the campus, graces the "Q" quadrangle. Its namesake, [United States Senator](/United_States_Senate) [Justin Morrill](/Justin_S._Morrill), is honored for his authorship of the pivotal 1862 [Morrill Land-Grant Acts](/Morrill_Land-Grant_Acts). [^24^]

Initially designated for single-gender occupancy, Lincoln Hall for male students and Manzanita Hall for female students were both erected in 1896. Prior to the construction of Lincoln Hall, male students found accommodation in the building that had previously housed the now-defunct [Bishop Whitaker's School for Girls](/Bishop_Whitaker%27s_School_for_Girls), which had ceased operations in 1894.

#### The Quad

The central gathering space of the campus is a verdant, tree-lined quadrangle, affectionately known as "the Quad." Situated in the southern sector of the campus, it is flanked by the imposing Morrill Hall and the distinguished Mackay School of Mines. Its design draws inspiration from the iconic quadrangle at the [University of Virginia](/University_of_Virginia). [^25^]

#### Herbarium

The [herbarium](/Herbarium) at UNR is a consolidated entity, comprising the collections of the Nevada Agricultural Experiment Station within the College of Agriculture and the Biology Department. Operating as a unified unit since 1978, it has benefited from the expertise of notable figures such as Patrick Beveridge Kennedy and [Amos Arthur Heller](/Amos_Arthur_Heller) at the experiment station, and Philip Augustus Lehenbauer, [Dwight Billings](/Dwight_Billings), Hugh Nelson Mozingo, Ira La Rivers, and [William Andrew Archer](/William_Andrew_Archer) within the biology department. [^26^]

#### Mackay Stadium

*   Main article: [Mackay Stadium](/Mackay_Stadium)

Mackay Stadium serves as the home turf for the university's football team. The contemporary Mackay Stadium, completed in 1966, initially offered seating for 7,500 spectators. Over the past fifteen years, the facility has undergone several expansions, significantly increasing its capacity to now accommodate 30,000 fans.

#### E.L. Wiegand Fitness Center

In June 2015, UNR embarked on the construction of a new, expansive 108,000-square-foot fitness center, christened the E.L. Wiegand Fitness Center. Inaugurated in February 2017, this facility is accessible to students as part of their annual tuition and fees. It features four floors, encompassing a gymnasium with three basketball courts, dedicated areas for weightlifting and cardio training, spaces for fitness classes, stadium-style stairs, and an indoor running track. The total cost of this ambitious project amounted to $46 million. [^27^] [^28^]

#### Lake Tahoe Campus

UNR's presence extends to its Lake Tahoe campus, named in honor of businessman Wayne L. Prim. This campus operates on the grounds of the former Sierra Nevada University. Currently, its primary function is research, augmented by two graduate programs in interdisciplinary arts and creative writing. [^29^] A significant development is slated for the fall of 2026 with the introduction of a nursing program, marking the first bachelor's degree offering since the closure of SNU. [^30^]

#### Sustainability

Since its inception in the fall of 2008, UNR's sustainability committee has been diligently engaged in gathering data and formulating a comprehensive plan to foster a more environmentally conscious campus. [^31^] Notable initiatives include robust recycling programs and efforts to maintain the campus's green spaces. A significant portion of the university's bus fleet operates on [biodiesel](/Biodiesel) fuel, and the campus bicycle program has witnessed a marked increase in user participation. University food services have committed 1% of their meal plan revenue to support sustainable initiatives on campus. [^32^] To curb energy consumption, UNR has installed solar panels on the Joe Crowley Student Union and constructed its first [LEED-accredited](/LEED) building. [^33^] The university's dedication to sustainability has earned it recognition among the nation's most eco-friendly colleges, [^34^] receiving an overall grade of "B+" on the [Sustainable Endowment Institute](/Sustainable_Endowments_Institute)'s College Sustainability Report Card in 2010. [^35^]

### Athletics

For athletic purposes, the university is simply referred to as Nevada, and its sports teams are known as the Wolf Pack. They compete vigorously in the NCAA's [Division I](/NCAA_Division_I), with football participating in the [FBS](/NCAA_Division_I_Football_Bowl_Subdivision) subdivision, and all sports aligned within the [Mountain West Conference](/Mountain_West_Conference).

A [Nevada Wolf Pack baseball](/Nevada_Wolf_Pack_baseball) player is captured in action, scoring a [run](/Run_(baseball)) during a 2011 game played in [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles).

#### Men's Basketball

*   Main article: [Nevada Wolf Pack men's basketball](/Nevada_Wolf_Pack_men%27s_basketball)

The Wolf Pack men's basketball team achieved a significant milestone in March 2004 by qualifying for the [NCAA tournament](/NCAA_Division_I_men%27s_basketball_tournament) and advancing to the [Sweet Sixteen](/NCAA_Division_I_men%27s_basketball_tournament) for the first time in the university's history. This success was followed by a repeat appearance in the tournament in 2005, where they defeated [Texas](/University_of_Texas_at_Austin) in the opening round before being eliminated by the eventual national runner-up, [Illinois](/University_of_Illinois_at_Urbana%E2%80%93Champaign). In 2006, the team entered the tournament as a No. 5 seed but suffered an unexpected first-round defeat to former [Big Sky Conference](/Big_Sky_Conference) rival [Montana](/University_of_Montana). The 2006–07 season commenced with the team ranked 24th nationally. A key figure during this successful period was star player [Nick Fazekas](/Nick_Fazekas). In 2007, Nevada reached a historic No. 9 ranking in men's basketball, its highest position ever.

#### Football

*   Main article: [Nevada Wolf Pack football](/Nevada_Wolf_Pack_football)

The football team plays its home games at [Mackay Stadium](/Mackay_Stadium). The current iteration of Mackay Stadium was completed in 1966, with an initial seating capacity of 7,500. Over the years, the stadium has undergone numerous expansions, now boasting a capacity of 30,000. In 2005, Nevada shared the WAC Title. The 2010 season marked a peak for the program, with Nevada finishing ranked No. 11 in the AP Poll and No. 13 in the BCS standings. A pivotal victory that season saw them stun Boise State 34–31, effectively ending the Broncos' hopes for a potential BCS title bid and securing another WAC title for Nevada.

#### Conference Affiliations

Nevada became a member of the [Mountain West Conference](/Mountain_West_Conference) in 2012. [^36^]

Prior to this, the university participated in the following conferences:

*   1954–1968 – [Northern California Athletic Conference](/Northern_California_Athletic_Conference)
*   1969–1978 – [West Coast Conference](/West_Coast_Conference) (while maintaining football as an independent team)
*   1979–1991 – [Big Sky](/Big_Sky_Conference) (this involved a conference affiliation swap with [Gonzaga University](/Gonzaga_University), which had discontinued its football program in 1941)
*   1992–1998 – [Big West](/Big_West_Conference)
*   1999–2012 – [WAC](/Western_Athletic_Conference)

### Student Media

The University of Nevada, Reno supports a vibrant ecosystem of student media organizations, providing essential platforms for student expression and journalistic endeavors. These include [The Nevada Sagebrush](/The_Nevada_Sagebrush), Wolf Pack Radio, Insight Magazine (formerly known as Artemisia), and The Brushfire Literature & Arts Journal. [^38^]

#### The Nevada Sagebrush

[The Nevada Sagebrush](/The_Nevada_Sagebrush) serves as the university's editorially independent, monthly student newspaper. Prior to 2004, the publication was simply known as the Sagebrush. [^39^] The newspaper has garnered significant recognition for its quality, achieving the prestigious [Associated Collegiate Press](/Associated_Collegiate_Press) [Pacemaker Award](/National_Pacemaker_Awards) seven times. These accolades were awarded in 2007, [^40^] 2008, [^41^] 2009, [^42^] 2010, [^43^] 2011, [^44^] 2012, [^45^] and most recently in 2015. [^46^]

#### Wolf Pack Radio

Wolf Pack Radio is the official student-run streaming-audio radio broadcast of Nevada. This station curates musical selections and produces a variety of radio shows tailored for the student body, accessible through its official website. In partnership with [KWNK](/KWNK-LP), Wolf Pack Radio also broadcasts its student-created programming on FM frequencies within the Reno area. [^47^]

The university was initially issued a license for station KOJ on May 1, 1922, [^48^] marking the first broadcasting station in the state of Nevada. However, it appears that KOJ never actually transmitted any broadcasts, [^49^] and its license, though granted for a three-month period, was officially canceled on June 7 of the same year. [^50^]

#### Insight Magazine

The university also provides support for Insight Magazine, a publication dedicated to photography and lifestyle content for the university community. [^51^] Prior to the summer of 2008, Insight Magazine was known as Artemisia. Under the Artemisia banner, the magazine served as the university yearbook, a tradition dating back to 1896. [^52^]

#### Brushfire

Established in 1950, Brushfire is a literature and arts journal committed to promoting the humanities among Nevada students. [^53^]

